SIMPLE: sunday
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Sunday
<hw>Sun"day</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>sunnandaeg</ets>; <ets>sunne</ets>, gen. <ets>sunnan</ets>, the sun
+ <ets>daeg</ets> day; akin to D. <ets>zondag</ets>, G.
<ets>sonntag</ets>; -- so called because this day was anciently
dedicated to the <ets>sun</ets>, or to its worship. See <er>Sun</er>,
and <er>Day</er>.]</ety> <def>The first day of the week, -- consecrated
among Christians to rest from secular employments, and to religious
worship; the Christian Sabbath; the Lord's Day.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Advent Sunday</b></col>, <col><b>Low
Sunday</b></col>, <col><b>Passion Sunday</b></col></mcol>, <cd>etc. See
under <er>Advent</er>, <er>Low</er>, etc.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- See <er>Sabbath</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sunday</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Sunday
<hw>Sun"day</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Belonging to the Christian
Sabbath.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Sunday letter</b></col>. <cd>See <cref>Dominical
letter</cref>, under <er>Dominical</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Sunday
school</b></col>. <cd>See under <er>School</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Sunder</ent>⟦br⟧
